insert into public.cards (id, front, back, topic, subtopic, level) values
('bat-001', 'How does MapReduce work? Describe the map, shuffle, and reduce phases.', 'MapReduce: a programming model for processing large datasets in parallel across a cluster. Input: files on a distributed filesystem (HDFS/GFS). Three phases: (1) Map: for each input record, the user-defined map function emits zero or more key-value pairs. Runs in parallel across all input file blocks. (2) Shuffle (framework-handled): framework collects all values for each key across all mapper outputs, sorts them by key, and routes them to the appropriate reducer. Network-intensive. (3) Reduce: for each unique key, the user-defined reduce function receives the key and all its values, and produces output. Runs in parallel across different keys. Output: written back to distributed filesystem. Key property: input is read-only — failures can be retried safely by re-running the map/reduce on the same input. Fault tolerance: failed tasks are automatically retried on other nodes. Contrast with stream: batch processes bounded input (yesterday''s data) on a schedule; stream processes unbounded input continuously.', 'batch_processing', 'MapReduce', 'L1'),
('bat-002', 'Compare reduce-side joins vs. map-side joins in MapReduce. When is each appropriate?', 'Reduce-side join (sort-merge join): mapper tags each record with its source dataset; shuffle groups all records with the same key together at the same reducer; reducer performs the join. No assumptions about data size or sort order. Handles any join size. Downside: expensive shuffle across network; all data must be transferred. Map-side join (broadcast hash join): one dataset small enough to fit in memory. The small dataset is loaded as a hash table into every mapper''s memory. Each mapper joins its input records against the in-memory hash table locally — no shuffle needed. Much faster for small-large joins. Partitioned map-side join: both datasets are partitioned and sorted the same way. Mapper only needs to hold one partition of the small dataset. Avoids full broadcast. When to use: reduce-side = large-large joins where both datasets are big; broadcast = small-large joins (e.g., user info table < 1 GB, event log is TBs); partitioned map-side = medium-large joins where both are sorted by the same key. Modern systems (Spark, Flink) choose join strategy automatically based on dataset size statistics.', 'batch_processing', 'joins', 'L2'),
('bat-003', 'What limitations of MapReduce did systems like Spark and Flink address?', 'MapReduce limitations: (1) Materializes intermediate state: every MapReduce job writes output to HDFS before the next job reads it. For multi-step pipelines (10+ jobs), this creates enormous I/O overhead — slow and expensive. (2) Batch-only: no native streaming support. (3) High latency: even a small query requires a full batch job. Spark improvements: in-memory RDDs (Resilient Distributed Datasets) — intermediate results stay in memory across operations, not written to disk between steps. Lazy evaluation — operations build a logical plan; execution starts only when output is needed, enabling optimization. For fault tolerance: recompute lost partitions from lineage (which operations created them) rather than writing checkpoints. Flink improvements: true streaming-first with bounded (batch) as special case; pipelined execution (operators process data as it arrives, without waiting for upstream to finish); exactly-once semantics with Chandy-Lamport snapshots. Common benefits of both: higher-level APIs (DataFrames, SQL, Dataset); automatic join strategy selection; better resource utilization. MapReduce is now largely deprecated for interactive analytics — Spark/Flink dominate.', 'batch_processing', 'beyond-MapReduce', 'L3'),
('con-001', 'What is the distributed consensus problem? What four properties must a consensus algorithm satisfy?', 'Consensus: getting multiple nodes to agree on a single value, even when some nodes may fail. Formalized as: nodes propose values; the algorithm decides on one. Four properties: (1) Uniform agreement: no two nodes decide differently. (2) Integrity: no node decides twice. (3) Validity: the decided value was actually proposed by some node (no fabricated values). (4) Termination: every non-crashed node eventually decides (liveness — ensures the system makes progress). Agreement + integrity = safety: everyone agrees on the same valid outcome. Termination = liveness: the system doesn''t get stuck forever. Trade-off: if all nodes crash, no algorithm can decide; at least a majority must be functioning for termination to be achievable.', 'consensus', 'definition', 'L1'),
('con-002', 'How does Two-Phase Commit (2PC) work? What is its fundamental limitation?', '2PC guarantees atomic commit across multiple nodes (all commit or all abort). Phases: Phase 1 — Prepare: coordinator sends ''prepare'' to all participants; each participant checks if it can commit and responds yes/no, then logs its promise. Phase 2 — Commit/Abort: if all say yes, coordinator logs ''commit'' decision, then sends commit to all. If any say no, coordinator sends abort. Key property: a participant that votes ''yes'' in Phase 1 cannot unilaterally abort — it must wait for coordinator''s Phase 2 decision. Fundamental limitation: 2PC is a blocking protocol. If the coordinator crashes after participants vote ''yes'' but before Phase 2, participants are stuck ''in doubt'' — they cannot commit or abort, and they hold locks indefinitely. Recovery requires the coordinator to come back and replay its log. This makes 2PC a single point of failure at the coordinator level.', 'consensus', '2PC', 'L1'),
('con-003', 'What is linearizability? How does it differ from serializability?', 'Linearizability (also called atomic consistency or strong consistency): a guarantee that the system behaves as if there is only a single copy of data, and all operations happen atomically at a specific point in time. Reads always return the most recently written value; concurrent operations appear to happen in some sequential order consistent with real time. Analogy: a linearizable system looks like a single-threaded single-machine database. Serializability (transactions): a guarantee that concurrent transactions execute in some serial order — but that order need not be consistent with real time (a transaction starting before another can be serialized after it). Difference: linearizability applies to individual read/write operations and concerns real-time ordering. Serializability applies to multi-operation transactions and concerns isolation from concurrent transactions. They are orthogonal — a database can provide neither, one, or both (the combination is called strict serializability or strong one-copy serializability).', 'consensus', 'linearizability', 'L1'),
('con-004', 'How does Raft achieve fault-tolerant consensus? Describe epoch numbers and the two-round voting process.', 'Raft and similar algorithms (Viewstamped Replication, Zab) implement total order broadcast (equivalent to repeated consensus). Key insight: leaders are used internally, but no single leader is guaranteed unique — multiple leader candidates can exist momentarily. Epoch numbers (called term in Raft, ballot in Paxos, view in VR): monotonically increasing integer assigned to each leadership period. Guarantees: within each epoch, the leader is unique; if two leaders from different epochs conflict, higher epoch wins. Two-round voting: Round 1 (leader election): candidates collect votes from a quorum (majority). A node votes only if the candidate has a higher epoch than anything it has seen. Round 2 (proposal): leader collects a quorum of votes for its proposed value. Critical overlap: the quorums for both rounds must overlap by at least one node. This ensures that if a proposal''s quorum doesn''t reveal a higher epoch, no newer leader election has occurred — the current leader can safely decide. Contrast with 2PC: 2PC coordinator is not elected (SPOF); consensus algorithms need only a majority, not all nodes.', 'consensus', 'raft', 'L2'),
('con-005', 'What is total order broadcast, and how is it equivalent to consensus?', 'Total order broadcast (atomic broadcast): a protocol requiring that messages be delivered exactly once, to all nodes, in the same order. Properties: (1) Reliable delivery: no message is lost — if delivered to one node, delivered to all. (2) Total ordering: all nodes receive messages in the same order. Equivalence to consensus: Total order broadcast is equivalent to repeatedly running consensus — each ''round'' of consensus decides the next message in the total order. Conversely, given total order broadcast, you can implement consensus: propose a value by broadcasting it; the first value in the total order is the consensus decision. Connection to replication: single-leader replication is essentially total order broadcast — leader decides order of writes; followers apply in same order. ZooKeeper and etcd implement total order broadcast (using Zab and Raft respectively) and expose it as linearizable operations (compare-and-set, leader election, distributed locks).', 'consensus', 'total-order-broadcast', 'L2'),
('con-006', '2PC is ''over 10x slower than single-node transactions'' in MySQL. Why? And what happens when the coordinator crashes mid-protocol?', 'Performance cost of 2PC: (1) Extra network round trips: Phase 1 (coordinator → all participants → coordinator) + Phase 2 (coordinator → all participants), vs. single-node''s local commit. (2) Disk fsync per phase: each participant must fsync its vote (Phase 1) and its commit record (Phase 2) to survive crashes — disk I/O is the main cost. (3) Lock holding: participants hold row-level locks throughout the protocol — from Phase 1 vote until Phase 2 commit. Coordinator crash: if coordinator crashes after Phase 1 votes but before Phase 2 decision, participants are ''in doubt.'' They cannot decide — they don''t know if the coordinator committed or aborted. They must HOLD LOCKS until coordinator recovers. If coordinator recovery takes 20 minutes, locks are held 20 minutes. If coordinator log is corrupted, locks may be held FOREVER until administrator manually intervenes. This is why 2PC is called a blocking atomic commit protocol. XA transactions (heterogeneous distributed transactions): use the standard XA C API; the coordinator is embedded in the application process (makes coordinator a SPOF if app crashes); orphaned in-doubt transactions are a known operational hazard.', 'consensus', '2PC', 'L3'),
('con-007', 'ZooKeeper and etcd implement consensus — but application developers rarely use them directly. What do they provide and how are they used?', 'ZooKeeper/etcd are coordination services, not general-purpose databases. They hold small amounts of data (fits in memory, persisted to disk) replicated via total order broadcast (Zab for ZooKeeper, Raft for etcd). Services provided: (1) Linearizable atomic operations: compare-and-set (CAS) — atomically writes a value only if it currently matches expected value. Used for leader election (first to CAS ''leader'' node wins). (2) Operations ordering + epochs: monotonically increasing transaction IDs (zxid in ZK, revision in etcd) serve as fencing tokens — any request with an older token is rejected, preventing split-brain writes. (3) Failure detection: sessions with heartbeats; ZooKeeper marks a node as failed if its session expires — triggers ephemeral node deletion, notifying other nodes. (4) Change notifications: clients subscribe to znodes; get notified of leader changes without constant polling. Used indirectly by: HBase, Hadoop YARN, Kafka, Kubernetes (etcd), OpenStack Nova. Application developers typically use ZK/etcd through higher-level abstractions like Curator (ZooKeeper client library) rather than raw ZK API.', 'consensus', 'zookeeper', 'L3'),
('con-008', 'What are the key limitations of consensus algorithms that prevent them from being used everywhere?', 'Despite providing strong guarantees, consensus algorithms have costs: (1) Performance: voting on proposals before decisions = synchronous replication overhead. Each round trip adds latency. Many databases use asynchronous replication (accepting data loss risk) for better throughput. (2) Strict majority required: to tolerate f failures you need 2f+1 nodes. A network partition leaves the minority partition completely blocked (cannot make progress). (3) Static membership: most consensus algorithms assume a fixed set of voting nodes. Dynamic membership (adding/removing nodes) requires separate complex protocols. (4) Timeout-based failure detection: in variable-latency networks (especially geo-distributed), nodes falsely declare leaders dead due to transient delays — causing unnecessary elections that degrade performance. (5) Network sensitivity: Raft can get into situations where leadership bounces between two nodes if one network link is consistently unreliable — system makes no progress. Rule of thumb: use consensus for leader election, distributed locks, and configuration management (small amounts of critical coordination data). Don''t use ZooKeeper/etcd as your primary database.', 'consensus', 'consensus-limitations', 'L4'),
('con-009', '2PC requires unanimous agreement; Raft only requires a majority. Why does 2PC exist as a protocol if it is strictly weaker than consensus (it can block indefinitely)? When is 2PC appropriate?', 'Why 2PC is weaker but still used: 2PC solves a different problem than consensus — atomic commit across heterogeneous systems (different databases, message brokers). Consensus algorithms (Raft, Paxos) assume all nodes run the same software and protocol. XA/2PC is a general interface that any database can implement. The blocking behavior is a known trade-off — accepted for cross-system atomicity that would be impossible to achieve otherwise. FLP impossibility: Fischer, Lynch, Patterson (1985) proved that in an asynchronous system, no deterministic consensus algorithm can guarantee both safety and liveness in the presence of even one crashed node. Consensus algorithms like Raft get around this by using timeouts (randomized election timeouts), which are technically unsafe but work in practice. 2PC avoids this problem by blocking rather than violating safety — it never makes an incorrect decision; it just might get stuck. When 2PC is appropriate: cross-database atomic operations (e.g., write to PostgreSQL AND send Kafka message atomically); heterogeneous systems where all parties cannot share a consensus protocol; XA transactions for enterprise middleware. When NOT: don''t use 2PC within a single distributed database that already has internal consensus — use the DB''s internal transaction mechanism instead.', 'consensus', '2PC-vs-consensus', 'L5'),
('ds-001', 'What is a B-tree and why is it used for database indexes rather than a binary BST?', 'B-tree: a self-balancing m-way search tree where each node can have up to m children and m-1 keys. All leaf nodes are at the same depth (perfectly balanced). Why not BST for databases: (1) Disk I/O dominance: each node access = one disk read. BST nodes hold 1 key → O(log₂ n) disk reads for n records. B-tree nodes hold hundreds of keys → O(log_m n) disk reads. For 1 billion records: BST needs ~30 disk reads; B-tree (m=500) needs ~4. (2) Cache efficiency: B-tree nodes sized to match disk pages (4–16 KB) → reads are aligned to disk block boundaries. B+ tree variant (used in most DBs): all data stored in leaf nodes; internal nodes hold only keys for routing. Leaf nodes linked as a doubly-linked list → efficient range scans. Operations: search O(log n), insert O(log n), delete O(log n). Used by: PostgreSQL, MySQL InnoDB, SQLite, Oracle.', 'data_structures', 'trees', 'L1'),
('ds-002', 'How do hash tables work? Compare open addressing vs. chaining for collision resolution.', 'Hash table: maps keys to values via a hash function. hash(key) → index in an array. O(1) average-case for get/put/delete. Collision: two different keys hash to the same index. Resolution strategies: Chaining (separate chaining): each array slot holds a linked list of (key, value) pairs. Simple but memory-inefficient (pointer overhead). Worst case O(n) if all keys collide. Used by Java HashMap (with tree conversion at 8 entries per bucket — O(log n) worst case). Open addressing: on collision, probe for next empty slot. Probing strategies: Linear probing: check index+1, +2, ... → clustering problem (long runs of occupied slots). Quadratic probing: check index+1², +2², ... → reduces clustering. Double hashing: use second hash function for step size → better distribution. Clustering is the enemy: when load factor is high (>0.7), collisions chain, performance degrades. Resize (rehash) when load factor exceeds threshold. Java HashMap resizes at 0.75. Robin Hood hashing: displace entries that are ''closer to home'' with entries that are ''farther from home'' → more uniform probe lengths.', 'data_structures', 'hash-tables', 'L1'),
('ds-003', 'How does a binary heap work? How is it used to implement a priority queue?', 'Binary heap: a complete binary tree where every node satisfies the heap property. Min-heap: parent ≤ children (root = minimum). Max-heap: parent ≥ children (root = maximum). Stored as an array: node at index i has children at 2i+1 and 2i+2, parent at ⌊(i-1)/2⌋. No pointers needed — implicit structure. Operations: peek (find min/max): O(1) — root of array. insert: append to end, sift up (swap with parent while heap property violated). O(log n). extract-min/max: replace root with last element, remove last, sift down. O(log n). build heap (heapify): given n elements, build heap in O(n) — not O(n log n). Heapsort: build heap O(n), extract max n times O(n log n) = O(n log n) total, O(1) space. Priority queue: min-heap where highest-priority item dequeued first. Used in: Dijkstra''s algorithm, A*, Huffman coding, task schedulers, OS process scheduling, event-driven simulations. Java PriorityQueue: min-heap. To get max-heap: PriorityQueue with reversed comparator.', 'data_structures', 'heaps', 'L2'),
('ds-004', 'Compare BFS and DFS. When is each appropriate? What are their key applications?', 'BFS (Breadth-First Search): explores level by level using a queue. Visits all nodes at distance d before distance d+1. Time: O(V+E), Space: O(V) for the queue. Key applications: (1) Shortest path in unweighted graph — BFS from source; first time a node is reached, that''s the shortest path. (2) Connected components in undirected graph. (3) Bipartite graph check. (4) Web crawlers (level-order exploration). DFS (Depth-First Search): explores as deep as possible before backtracking. Uses a stack (or recursion). Time: O(V+E), Space: O(V) for recursion stack (can be O(h) where h=height). Key applications: (1) Topological sort (DAGs) — DFS finish order reversed = topological order. (2) Cycle detection in directed graph. (3) Strongly connected components (Kosaraju''s/Tarjan''s). (4) Maze solving. (5) Tree traversal (preorder/inorder/postorder). Choose BFS when: finding shortest paths, exploring nearby nodes first. Choose DFS when: exploring all paths, detecting cycles, topological ordering. Memory: BFS can use O(V) memory for wide graphs; DFS uses O(height) — better for tall/narrow graphs. Dijkstra (weighted shortest path): BFS with a priority queue instead of a regular queue.', 'data_structures', 'graphs', 'L2'),
('ds-005', 'How do you implement an O(1) LRU cache? What data structures does it require?', 'LRU (Least Recently Used) cache: evicts the item that was least recently accessed when the cache is full. O(1) get and put required. Data structures: HashMap + Doubly Linked List. HashMap: key → node pointer. O(1) lookup by key. Doubly linked list: nodes ordered by recency (most recent at head, least recent at tail). O(1) move-to-front and remove-from-tail (doubly linked for O(1) delete given pointer). Operations: get(key): if key in map → move node to head → return value. If not → return -1. put(key, value): if key in map → update value, move to head. If not → create new node at head, add to map. If at capacity → remove tail node, remove from map. All O(1) due to: HashMap for O(1) key lookup (get the node pointer directly); doubly linked list for O(1) insertion/deletion given a pointer (no traversal needed). Java: LinkedHashMap with access order = true provides LRU semantics out of the box. LFU (Least Frequently Used): evicts the item with the lowest access count. More complex: requires a frequency map + per-frequency doubly linked list + tracking minimum frequency. O(1) achievable with this structure.', 'data_structures', 'lru-cache', 'L2'),
('ds-006', 'What is a Bloom filter, when would you use it, and what is its trade-off?', 'Bloom filter: a space-efficient probabilistic data structure that answers ''is element X in the set?'' It can say: ''Definitely NOT in set'' (no false negatives) or ''Probably in set'' (possible false positives). Structure: a bit array of m bits + k independent hash functions. Add(x): hash x with all k functions → set k bits to 1. Query(x): hash x with all k functions → if any bit is 0, x is definitely not in set; if all bits are 1, x is probably in set. False positive rate: depends on m (bits), n (elements), k (hash functions). Tunable — more bits → lower false positive rate. No deletion (setting bits to 0 could affect other elements). Use cases: (1) Database query optimization: before reading disk, check if key might exist. Avoids expensive disk reads for non-existent keys (Cassandra, RocksDB, BigTable). (2) Web cache: ''have I seen this URL before?'' (web crawlers). (3) Spam filters: ''is this email address known spam?''. (4) Akamai CDN: avoid caching one-hit-wonder URLs. Rule of thumb: ~10 bits per element achieves ~1% false positive rate. Cuckoo filter: an alternative that supports deletion with better lookup performance.', 'data_structures', 'bloom-filters', 'L3'),
('ds-007', 'What is a skip list, and why is it used in some databases instead of a balanced BST?', 'Skip list: a probabilistic data structure providing O(log n) average search, insert, and delete on a sorted linked list, without complex rotations. Structure: multiple levels of linked lists. Bottom level = complete sorted list. Each higher level = subset of elements from level below (promoted with probability p = 0.5 usually). Search: start at highest level, move right while next key ≤ target, drop down a level, repeat. Average O(log n) — acts like binary search on a linked list. Why skip lists over balanced BSTs (AVL, Red-Black): (1) Simpler implementation — no rotations or rebalancing code. (2) Better concurrent performance — fine-grained locking per node rather than tree-wide rebalancing lock. (3) Range scans: just traverse bottom linked list — O(k) for k results after O(log n) search. Used in: Redis (sorted sets are skip lists), Apache Cassandra (memtable), MemSQL, LevelDB memtable. ConcurrentSkipListMap in Java: lock-free skip list for concurrent sorted map. O(log n) with better concurrency than ConcurrentHashMap for ordered access.', 'data_structures', 'skip-lists', 'L3'),
('ds-008', 'Compare AVL trees and Red-Black trees. When does each perform better?', 'Both are self-balancing BSTs maintaining O(log n) operations. AVL tree: strictly balanced — height difference between left/right subtrees ≤ 1 for every node. Rotations: single or double rotation to restore balance. More rotations on insert/delete. Balanced factor stored per node. Red-Black tree: loosely balanced — no path from root to leaf is more than 2x longer than any other. 5 properties: (1) every node is red or black, (2) root is black, (3) leaves (null) are black, (4) red node has black children, (5) all paths from node to descendant leaves have same number of black nodes. Fewer rotations on insert/delete (at most 2 rotations). Performance comparison: AVL: faster lookups (shorter height, more balanced). Better for read-heavy workloads. Red-Black: faster inserts and deletes (fewer rotations). Better for write-heavy workloads. In practice: Red-Black used in: Java TreeMap, TreeSet; C++ std::map, std::set; Linux kernel''s virtual memory areas. AVL used in: database indexes where lookup speed matters most. Both O(log n) for all operations; the constant factor differs.', 'data_structures', 'trees', 'L4'),
('flt-001', 'What is a partial failure, and why is it the defining challenge of distributed systems?', 'Partial failure: in a distributed system, some parts of the system may fail while others continue working correctly — and it''s often non-obvious which parts have failed. In a single computer, either everything works or the whole machine crashes (deterministic behavior). In distributed systems, you might have: a network packet is lost but the sender doesn''t know if the receiver got it; a message is delayed arbitrarily; a node crashes mid-operation; a node is slow but not crashed (behaves like it crashed from others'' perspective). Nondeterminism: partial failures are nondeterministic. The same request might succeed on one try and fail on the next, with no code change. Networks in practice: packet loss, corruption, unbounded delays, asymmetric partitions (A can send to B, B cannot send to A), full datacenter failures. This is fundamentally different from writing software for a single machine — you must design for the possibility of partial failure at every layer.', 'distributed_systems_faults', 'networks', 'L1'),
('flt-002', 'Why can''t distributed systems rely on synchronized clocks? What are the two types of clocks and when is each appropriate?', 'Problem with synchronized clocks: NTP synchronization has uncertainty of tens of milliseconds on a good day; up to 100ms or more on a congested network. Computer clocks drift and must be corrected by NTP — they can jump forward or backward. Leap seconds: NTP may introduce a 1-second gap or repeat. Quartz oscillators drift 6ms/day. Two clock types: 1. Time-of-day clock (wall clock): returns current date and time. Synchronized to NTP. Can jump forward or backward on NTP correction. NOT suitable for measuring elapsed time or ordering events across nodes (skew makes comparisons unreliable). Use for: logging timestamps for human consumption, coarse scheduling. 2. Monotonic clock: returns a counter that always moves forward (never jumps back). Not synchronized across nodes — absolute value is meaningless. Suitable for: measuring duration of operations within a single process (nanosecond precision). Use for: timeouts, performance measurements. Key danger: using time-of-day clocks for ordering distributed events. Last Write Wins (LWW) based on timestamps is unreliable — clock skew can cause newer writes to appear older. Alternative: Lamport timestamps or vector clocks for causal ordering without relying on wall clocks.', 'distributed_systems_faults', 'clocks', 'L2'),
('flt-003', 'What is a process pause, and why does it invalidate leader leases in distributed systems?', 'Process pause: a running process can be ''paused'' for an arbitrary duration by: GC (garbage collection) stop-the-world pauses — typically milliseconds but can be seconds for large heaps; VM live migration — hypervisor pauses the VM briefly while migrating to another host; OS context switching to other processes; disk I/O blocking the process; heavy CPU load. Problem with leader leases: a leader acquires a lease (distributed lock with expiry, e.g., 30 seconds). Leader assumes it''s still the leader during the lease period. But: if the leader process pauses (e.g., GC pause for 35 seconds) during the lease, the lease expires and a new leader is elected. The paused process resumes, still thinks it''s leader, and issues writes — now two leaders exist. The paused process doesn''t know time has passed. Solution — fencing tokens: whenever a lock is acquired, the lock service returns a monotonically increasing token. Any write to the storage service must include the token; the storage service rejects writes with older tokens than it has already seen. This prevents an old leader''s writes from being accepted even if it doesn''t know it''s no longer leader.', 'distributed_systems_faults', 'process-pauses', 'L2'),
('flt-004', 'What are the common system models for distributed systems, and why do they matter for algorithm correctness?', 'Node behavior models: 1. Crash-stop: a node either works correctly or stops permanently (never sends incorrect data). Simplest model. 2. Crash-recovery: a node can crash and restart; it may have durable state (disk) that survives crashes but not in-memory state. Most real systems assume this. 3. Byzantine faults: a node can behave arbitrarily — sending incorrect, malicious, or contradictory messages. Byzantine fault-tolerant (BFT) algorithms exist but are expensive; required for: blockchain consensus, aerospace, nuclear systems. In practice most distributed DBs assume crash-recovery (not Byzantine). Network timing models: 1. Synchronous: bounded message delay and processing time. Easy to reason about; rarely true in practice. 2. Asynchronous: no timing guarantees whatsoever — messages can be delayed arbitrarily. FLP impossibility applies. 3. Partially synchronous (most real systems): usually behaves synchronously but occasionally has unbounded delays. Most practical distributed algorithms assume partial synchrony — they rely on timeouts, knowing timeouts may be wrong sometimes. Algorithm properties: Safety (nothing bad ever happens): must hold even in asynchronous systems with crashes. Liveness (something good eventually happens): only needs to hold in partially synchronous systems. Engineers design for safety always; liveness under ''good enough'' conditions.', 'distributed_systems_faults', 'system-models', 'L3'),
('par-001', 'What is partitioning (sharding) in distributed databases, and why is it needed?', 'Partitioning (also called sharding) means splitting a large dataset across multiple nodes, so each node holds only a subset of the data. It is needed when the dataset is too large to fit on a single machine, or when query throughput exceeds what one machine can handle. Each partition is like a small database of its own, though the operations that touch multiple partitions are more complex. Partitioning is usually combined with replication: each partition is replicated across multiple nodes for fault tolerance.', 'partitioning', 'basics', 'L1'),
('par-002', 'What are the two primary partitioning strategies, and what are their trade-offs?', '1. Key-range partitioning: partitions are assigned a continuous range of sorted keys (like encyclopedia volumes). Enables efficient range queries — keys in one range are co-located. Risk: hot spots if workload is skewed (e.g., writing today''s timestamp key all to one partition). Used by: HBase, RethinkDB, Bigtable. 2. Hash partitioning: a hash function is applied to the key; the hash determines the partition. Distributes keys evenly — reduces hot spots. Loses range query ability (must scatter-gather to all partitions). Used by: Cassandra (compound key: hash first part, range on rest), MongoDB hash sharding. Skew mitigation: if one key is extremely hot (celebrity user), append a random number prefix to split it across N partitions — reads must then combine from all N.', 'partitioning', 'strategies', 'L1'),
('par-003', 'What are the two approaches to partitioning secondary indexes, and what are their trade-offs?', '1. Document-partitioned (local index): each partition maintains its own secondary index covering only its documents. Writes are local — update only the partition that owns the document. Reads require scatter/gather across all partitions to find all matching documents — expensive for high-cardinality queries; prone to tail latency amplification. Used by: MongoDB, Riak, Cassandra, Elasticsearch. 2. Term-partitioned (global index): a global index covering all documents is itself partitioned by term. Reads are efficient — go only to the partition(s) holding the queried term. Writes are expensive — a single document write may affect many term-index partitions; global secondary indexes are usually updated asynchronously (may lag writes). Used by: Amazon DynamoDB (global secondary indexes), Riak search.', 'partitioning', 'secondary-indexes', 'L1'),
('par-004', 'What are the three main strategies for rebalancing partitions, and why is ''hash mod N'' a bad approach?', 'Why NOT hash mod N: if N (number of nodes) changes, almost all keys must be remapped — extremely expensive. Example: hash(key)=123456; with 10 nodes → node 6; with 11 nodes → node 3; with 12 nodes → node 0. Nearly every key moves on every node addition. Better strategies: 1. Fixed number of partitions: create many more partitions than nodes (e.g., 1000 partitions for 10 nodes). Adding a node steals a few partitions from existing nodes. Only partition-to-node assignment changes, not key-to-partition. Used by: Riak, Elasticsearch, Couchbase. 2. Dynamic partitioning: partitions split when they exceed a size threshold (HBase default: 10 GB), merge when they shrink. Size adapts to data volume. Pre-splitting avoids initial single-node bottleneck. 3. Proportional to nodes (Cassandra): fixed partitions per node; adding a node splits random existing partitions and takes half.', 'partitioning', 'rebalancing', 'L2'),
('par-005', 'How do clients know which node to contact for a partitioned database? Describe the three approaches to request routing.', 'Challenge: as partitions are rebalanced, the assignment of partitions to nodes changes. Clients must know where to send requests. Three approaches: 1. Any node with forwarding: client contacts any node; if that node doesn''t own the requested partition, it forwards the request to the correct node and relays the reply (gossip protocol). Used by: Cassandra, Riak. 2. Routing tier: a separate partition-aware load balancer or router receives all requests and forwards them to the correct node. 3. Client-side routing: clients are partition-aware and directly contact the correct node. Used by: MongoDB (mongos router), Kafka. Common coordination mechanism: ZooKeeper or etcd maintains authoritative partition-to-node mapping; nodes register themselves; clients and routing tiers subscribe to changes. HBase, Kafka, SolrCloud, Helix use ZooKeeper this way.', 'partitioning', 'request-routing', 'L2'),
('par-006', 'A social media platform has a celebrity with 50M followers. Every time they post, all writes go to the same partition. How would you mitigate this hot spot?', 'Root cause: hashing the celebrity''s user_id always produces the same hash → same partition, regardless of hash partitioning. Mitigation strategies: 1. Key splitting with random suffix: append a random 2-digit number (00–99) to the celebrity''s key on write, distributing writes across 100 sub-keys on different partitions. Trade-off: reads must now query all 100 sub-keys and combine results. Must track which keys are ''hot'' (can''t apply this to all keys — unnecessary overhead for low-volume users). 2. Dedicated partition: manually assign a separate partition for known hot entities (requires operational tooling). 3. Application-level caching: cache the celebrity''s posts in a read-heavy CDN/cache layer so partitions don''t absorb all reads. 4. Fan-out on write: pre-compute and push notifications to follower shards at write time (Twitter''s approach). This is an application-level trade-off, not solved by the DB partitioning scheme alone.', 'partitioning', 'strategies', 'L3'),
('par-007', 'You are designing a used-car marketplace with millions of listings. Users filter by color AND make simultaneously. Compare document-partitioned vs. term-partitioned secondary indexes for this query pattern.', 'Query: ''find all red Toyotas'' — requires matching on color:red AND make:Toyota simultaneously. Document-partitioned (local index): each partition has its own index. Query must scatter-gather to ALL partitions, collect matching document IDs from each, then intersect them. High latency (tail latency amplification); grows linearly with number of partitions. Suitable when most queries filter on partition key (e.g., partition by document_id, filter by document_id ranges). Term-partitioned (global index): index on color has one partition assignment; index on make has another. Query for red Toyotas goes to two partitions (color:red index, make:Toyota index), fetches doc IDs, intersects in application. Writes expensive — a new red Toyota must update both index partitions, possibly on different nodes. Index is usually updated asynchronously → short window where new listings aren''t searchable. Recommendation: for this query pattern, term-partitioned global indexes are better for read performance. Accept async index updates and handle the eventual-consistency window in the UI (e.g., ''listing may take a moment to appear in search'').', 'partitioning', 'secondary-indexes', 'L4'),
('par-008', 'Why is fully automatic partition rebalancing potentially dangerous? Give a concrete failure scenario.', 'Danger: automatic rebalancing combined with automatic failure detection can cause cascading failures. Scenario: Node A is temporarily slow (e.g., GC pause or network congestion). Other nodes observe slow responses and conclude Node A has failed. Automatic rebalancing triggers: partitions from Node A are redistributed to Nodes B, C, D. This rebalancing requires moving large amounts of data — now Nodes B, C, D are also overloaded with both serving requests AND accepting rebalancing data transfers. The added load causes Nodes B and C to slow down. Other nodes may now incorrectly conclude B and C are also failing, triggering more rebalancing. Potential outcome: a cascading failure that takes down the entire cluster, triggered by one temporarily slow node. Mitigation: require human approval for rebalancing (Couchbase, Riak, Voldemort generate a rebalancing plan automatically but require administrator to commit it). Rate-limit rebalancing bandwidth. Use circuit breakers to pause rebalancing if cluster health degrades during the process.', 'partitioning', 'rebalancing', 'L5'),
('rep-001', 'What is replication in distributed databases, and why is it used?', 'Replication means keeping a copy of the same data on multiple machines connected via a network. It is used to: (1) reduce latency by keeping data geographically close to users, (2) increase availability so the system continues working if some parts fail, and (3) scale read throughput by distributing read queries across multiple replicas. The core challenge is handling changes to replicated data.', 'replication', 'basics', 'L1'),
('rep-002', 'What is leader-based replication (master–slave replication)?', 'In leader-based replication: (1) one replica is designated the leader — all writes go to the leader first; (2) followers receive a replication log or change stream from the leader and apply writes in the same order; (3) reads can go to either the leader or any follower, but writes are only accepted by the leader. Used in PostgreSQL, MySQL, MongoDB, Kafka, and many others.', 'replication', 'leader-follower', 'L1'),
('rep-003', 'What is the difference between synchronous and asynchronous replication?', 'Synchronous: the leader waits for the follower to confirm receipt before reporting success to the client. Guarantees up-to-date copy on at least one follower, but if the follower is slow or down, the leader must block all writes. Asynchronous: the leader sends the change and does not wait for a response. Writes are faster and the leader can continue if followers fall behind, but writes may be lost if the leader fails before replication. Most systems use semi-synchronous: one follower synchronous, the rest asynchronous.', 'replication', 'sync-async', 'L1'),
('rep-004', 'What is replication lag, and what is eventual consistency?', 'Replication lag is the delay between a write being applied on the leader and being reflected on a follower. When reading from an asynchronous follower, you may see outdated data if the follower has fallen behind. This inconsistency is temporary — if writes stop, followers eventually catch up. This property is called eventual consistency: given enough time without new writes, all replicas converge to the same state. In normal operation lag is milliseconds; under load it can grow to seconds or minutes.', 'replication', 'lag', 'L1'),
('rep-005', 'Walk through the automatic failover process when a leader fails in leader-based replication.', '1. Detect leader failure: nodes use a timeout (e.g., 30 seconds without response) — no foolproof detection exists. 2. Elect new leader: either by election (majority vote) or appointment by a controller node; best candidate is the replica with the most up-to-date data. 3. Reconfigure clients to send writes to the new leader; old leader must become a follower when it returns. Key failure modes: (a) unreplicated writes from old leader may be lost or conflict, (b) split brain — two nodes both believe they are leader (dangerous: data corruption). Some systems use STONITH (Shoot The Other Node In The Head) fencing as a safeguard.', 'replication', 'leader-follower', 'L2'),
('rep-006', 'What are the four main approaches to implementing replication logs, and what are the key trade-offs?', '1. Statement-based: leader forwards every SQL statement (INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE) to followers. Problem: non-deterministic functions (NOW(), RAND()), autoincrement, side effects can produce different results on replicas. 2. WAL shipping: sends the exact write-ahead log bytes to followers. Problem: tightly coupled to storage engine format — version mismatches between leader and followers are not possible. 3. Logical (row-based) log: a separate log describing row-level changes (inserted/deleted/updated rows). Decoupled from storage engine — allows version mismatches and is easier to parse externally (basis for CDC). 4. Trigger-based: application-level replication via triggers/stored procedures. Most flexible but highest overhead and most bug-prone.', 'replication', 'replication-logs', 'L2'),
('rep-007', 'Describe the three replication lag consistency guarantees: read-after-write, monotonic reads, and consistent prefix reads.', '1. Read-after-write (read-your-writes): guarantees that a user who just submitted data will always see their own update when they read. Implementation: read from the leader for data the user may have modified; or track the user''s last write timestamp and route reads to replicas that have caught up to that timestamp. 2. Monotonic reads: if a user makes multiple reads in sequence, they will never see an older state after seeing a newer one (reads don''t go backward in time). Implementation: always route a given user''s reads to the same replica (e.g., hash of user ID). 3. Consistent prefix reads: if writes happen in a certain order, reads must see them in that order. Prevents causality violations (seeing the answer before the question). Challenge in partitioned databases where partitions operate independently.', 'replication', 'consistency-guarantees', 'L2'),
('rep-008', 'How does multi-leader replication work, and what are the main write conflict resolution strategies?', 'Multi-leader (active-active/master-master): multiple nodes accept writes; each leader replicates its changes to all other leaders. Main use cases: multi-datacenter deployments (leader in each DC reduces inter-datacenter latency), offline clients (each device acts as a leader). Core problem: the same data can be concurrently modified in different DCs — conflicts must be resolved. Resolution strategies: (1) Last Write Wins (LWW) by timestamp — dangerously prone to data loss due to clock skew; (2) replica ID precedence — also loses data; (3) merge values together; (4) record conflicts in explicit data structure and resolve later (application code). Advanced: CRDTs (conflict-free replicated data types) auto-resolve in a mathematically consistent way; Operational Transformation (used in Google Docs).', 'replication', 'multi-leader', 'L2'),
('rep-009', 'How does leaderless (Dynamo-style) replication work? Explain quorums and the w + r > n condition.', 'Leaderless: clients send writes to multiple replicas in parallel (or via a coordinator); any replica can accept writes; no failover concept. Used in Amazon Dynamo, Cassandra, Riak, Voldemort. Quorum reads/writes: with n replicas, require w write acknowledgments and r read responses. If w + r > n, at least one node in any read set must have the latest write. Example: n=3, w=2, r=2 → tolerates 1 unavailable node; n=5, w=3, r=3 → tolerates 2. Stale-value repair: (1) Read repair — on a read, compare versions from r replicas, write newer value back to stale ones; (2) Anti-entropy — background process that continuously copies missing data between replicas. Sloppy quorum: if designated n nodes are unreachable, write to other available nodes instead (hinted handoff), trading strict consistency for higher availability.', 'replication', 'leaderless', 'L2'),
('rep-010', 'What are the trade-offs between synchronous and asynchronous replication? When would you choose each?', 'Synchronous: strong durability guarantee — confirmed write is on ≥2 nodes. But: any single synchronous follower outage blocks all writes; latency increases because writes must wait for follower ACK. Choose when: data loss is unacceptable (financial transactions, legal records). Asynchronous: leader continues processing writes even if all followers fall behind. Write latency is lower. But: if leader fails before replicating, confirmed writes can be lost — durability guarantee is weakened. Choose when: write throughput and availability matter more than zero data loss (e.g., analytics ingestion, social media). Semi-synchronous (most real systems): one follower is synchronous, rest are async — at least two copies always up-to-date, writes don''t wait for all followers.', 'replication', 'sync-async', 'L3'),
('rep-011', 'Compare single-leader vs. multi-leader replication in a multi-datacenter deployment.', 'Single-leader multi-datacenter: all writes must cross the internet to the leader''s DC — adds significant write latency; inter-DC link is a bottleneck; if leader DC fails, failover is required. Multi-leader multi-datacenter: each DC has its own leader; writes are processed locally and asynchronously replicated to other DCs — inter-DC network delay hidden from users. DC failure handled independently; better performance and availability. But: write conflicts possible (same data modified concurrently in two DCs); conflict resolution is complex and error-prone; multi-leader is ''dangerous territory'' in many databases with subtle bugs (autoincrement, triggers, integrity constraints). Rule of thumb: avoid multi-leader unless single-leader performance in a multi-DC setup is demonstrably insufficient.', 'replication', 'multi-leader', 'L3'),
('rep-012', 'Even with w + r > n, can quorum reads always return the most recent write? What are the edge cases?', 'No — despite w + r > n, stale values can still be returned in several scenarios: (1) Sloppy quorum: writes go to non-designated nodes, breaking the overlap guarantee; (2) Concurrent writes: if two writes race, winner determined by LWW timestamp — susceptible to clock skew causing data loss; (3) Write partially replicated: a write succeeds on some replicas but fails on others (e.g., disk full) and is not rolled back; (4) Node failure restores old data: a node with new data fails and recovers from a replica with old data, dropping below w copies of the new value. Conclusion: Dynamo-style databases are optimized for eventual consistency; they do NOT generally provide strong guarantees like read-your-writes or monotonic reads from quorum reads alone. Stronger guarantees require transactions or consensus.', 'replication', 'leaderless', 'L3'),
('rep-013', 'A 5-node leader-follower MySQL cluster uses asynchronous replication. The leader crashes after committing 100 writes not yet replicated. A follower is promoted. What are the risks and how would you mitigate them?', 'Risks: (1) Data loss: the 100 unreplicated writes are permanently lost since asynchronous replication doesn''t guarantee durability. (2) Primary key reuse: if the old leader used autoincrement IDs for those 100 rows, the new leader may reissue the same IDs — causing collisions in external systems (e.g., cache, event store) referencing those IDs. (3) Split brain: if the old leader recovers and thinks it''s still primary, you have two leaders accepting writes — data corruption. Mitigations: (1) Use semi-synchronous replication (at least one synchronous follower) for critical data. (2) Implement STONITH/fencing to forcibly prevent old leader from accepting writes. (3) Use monotonically increasing epoch/term numbers (like Raft) to distinguish old vs. new leader. (4) Design application to handle idempotency and eventual re-sync rather than assuming zero loss.', 'replication', 'leader-follower', 'L4'),
('rep-014', 'You are designing a Cassandra cluster (leaderless) for a banking ledger. A colleague suggests n=3, w=1, r=1 for maximum performance. What''s wrong with this, and what would you recommend?', 'Problem with w=1, r=1: w + r = 2, which is NOT > n=3. This means a read and a write can go to entirely different nodes with zero overlap — stale reads guaranteed. Even worse for banking: a deposit (write) could be confirmed but not seen by a subsequent balance check (read). Recommendation for banking ledger: (1) Quorum: n=3, w=2, r=2 (w + r = 4 > 3) ensures at least one overlapping node; tolerates 1 node failure for both reads and writes. (2) Or strong consistency: w=3, r=1 — all writes to all nodes, fast reads; any node failure stops writes. (3) Consider that Cassandra''s LWW conflict resolution and lack of multi-row transactions may fundamentally make it unsuitable for a banking ledger regardless of quorum settings — a database with ACID transactions (PostgreSQL, CockroachDB) may be more appropriate. Leaderless is generally optimized for use cases tolerating eventual consistency.', 'replication', 'leaderless', 'L4'),
('rep-015', 'What is a split-brain scenario in leader-based replication, and why is it so dangerous? How do systems defend against it?', 'Split brain: two nodes both believe they are the leader simultaneously — typically occurs when a network partition makes the old leader unreachable to followers (who elect a new leader) but the old leader can still accept writes from clients. Danger: both leaders accept writes independently with no conflict resolution; data is permanently inconsistent and may be silently corrupted. Example: GitHub''s 2012 incident where MySQL replication lag caused a follower to be promoted while the old leader was still running — user data exposed to wrong accounts due to reused primary keys. Defenses: (1) Fencing tokens: each leadership epoch has a monotonically increasing token; the storage system rejects any write from a leader with a lower-numbered token. (2) STONITH (Shoot The Other Node In The Head): forcibly power off or network-isolate the old leader before promoting a new one. (3) Conservative timeout: wait longer before declaring a leader dead, reducing unnecessary elections. (4) Quorum-based leader election (Raft/Paxos): a new leader can only be elected with majority agreement, making it impossible for an isolated old leader to form a quorum.', 'replication', 'failover', 'L5'),
('rep-016', 'In a multi-leader all-to-all topology, why can messages arrive out of causal order, and how can this be detected?', 'Causality violation in all-to-all: Client A inserts a row on leader 1; Client B updates that row on leader 3. Due to differential network speeds, leader 2 may receive the UPDATE before the INSERT — applying an update to a non-existent row. Root cause: there is no global write ordering in multi-leader; attaching wall-clock timestamps is insufficient because clocks across nodes are not perfectly synchronized (as shown in Chapter 8). Detection and ordering: Version vectors (also called vector clocks) track which writes each replica has seen. Each node maintains a vector [v1, v2, ..., vn] where vi is the number of operations seen from replica i. On receiving a write, a node can determine if all causally preceding writes have been applied. Conflict detection and ordering in many real multi-leader systems (e.g., PostgreSQL BDR, MySQL Tungsten Replicator) is poorly implemented or not attempted.', 'replication', 'multi-leader', 'L5'),
('sto-001', 'What is an LSM-tree (Log-Structured Merge-tree)? Describe how writes and reads work.', 'LSM-tree: a write-optimized storage engine structure. Components: Memtable: in-memory sorted tree (e.g., red-black tree or AVL); all writes go here first. WAL: write-ahead log for crash recovery — memtable can be rebuilt from WAL on restart. SSTables: when memtable exceeds size threshold, it''s flushed to disk as a sorted, immutable SSTable file. Compaction: background process periodically merges SSTables, keeping only latest values for each key (like mergesort). Read path: check memtable → check most recent SSTable → older SSTables (in order). Use Bloom filters to avoid checking SSTables that definitely don''t contain a key. Write path: append to WAL → insert into memtable. Very fast (sequential writes). Read cost: potentially slow for keys not in memtable (must check multiple SSTables). Optimized by: Bloom filters, sparse in-memory index, block compression. Used by: LevelDB, RocksDB, Cassandra, HBase, Elasticsearch.', 'storage_engines', 'LSM-trees', 'L1'),
('sto-002', 'How does a B-tree storage engine work? How does it differ from LSM-trees?', 'B-tree: the standard storage engine for most relational databases (PostgreSQL, MySQL InnoDB, SQLite). Structure: tree of fixed-size pages (typically 4–16 KB), read/written one page at a time. Each page contains keys + pointers to child pages or references to values. Pages form a balanced tree; all leaf pages at same depth. Branching factor: number of references per page — typically several hundred. Height stays small: 4 levels can address 256 TB of data. Writes: find the leaf page containing the key → overwrite it in place. If page too full, split into two pages, update parent. Crash safety: WAL (write-ahead log) is written before modifying any page — on crash, incomplete operations are replayed. Reads: O(log n) — traverse from root to leaf. Generally faster reads than LSM for random point queries (fewer disk seeks). Writes: random I/O (overwrite in place) — slower than LSM''s sequential appends, especially on HDDs. Trade-off summary: B-trees = faster reads, slower writes. LSM-trees = faster writes, potentially slower reads. B-trees are preferred for read-heavy OLTP; LSM for write-heavy workloads.', 'storage_engines', 'B-trees', 'L1'),
('sto-003', 'What is write amplification in LSM-trees? Compare leveled vs. tiered compaction strategies.', 'Write amplification: a single logical write causes multiple physical writes to disk (WAL + memtable flush + compaction rewrites). Higher write amplification = higher disk I/O per user write = lower write throughput. Leveled compaction (LevelDB, RocksDB, Cassandra): SSTables organized into levels (L0, L1, L2...). Each level has a size limit 10x larger than the previous. Compaction merges SSTables from level N into level N+1. Result: each key appears at most once per level (except L0). Pros: reads efficient (fewer SSTables to check per level), space efficient. Cons: higher write amplification (data is compacted more aggressively). Tiered/size-tiered compaction (Cassandra also supports, Scylla): when enough SSTables of similar size accumulate, merge them into a larger SSTable. Pros: lower write amplification. Cons: more SSTables to check on reads (bloom filters help); higher space amplification (old data occupies space until compacted). Key metrics: write amplification (total bytes written / bytes of user data written), read amplification (disk reads per user read), space amplification (disk used / logical data size).', 'storage_engines', 'LSM-trees', 'L2'),
('sto-004', 'When would you choose an LSM-tree storage engine over a B-tree, and vice versa? Give specific workload scenarios.', 'Choose LSM-tree when: (1) Write-heavy workloads — high volume of inserts/updates; LSM''s sequential writes and batch compaction outperform B-tree''s random in-place overwrites, especially on HDDs and SSDs with limited write cycles. (2) Time-series / log data — append-heavy, rarely updated; LSM shines at continuous sequential inserts. (3) High write throughput requirements — metrics ingestion, IoT sensor data, event logging. (4) Compression is important — SSTables can be compressed more effectively than B-tree pages. Choose B-tree when: (1) Read-heavy workloads — point queries and range scans; each key exists in exactly one place (no need to check multiple SSTables). (2) Low read latency requirements — B-tree guarantees O(log n) reads; LSM can require checking multiple levels. (3) Transactions are critical — B-trees have simpler locking semantics (range locks on B-tree nodes); LSM MVCC is more complex. (4) Predictable performance — LSM compaction can cause write stalls when I/O is saturated; B-tree performance is more consistent. Hybrid: some databases use B-trees for indexes and LSM for row data (RocksDB as PostgreSQL''s FDW).', 'storage_engines', 'comparison', 'L3'),
('sto-005', 'Why are column-oriented storage engines better than row-oriented for analytics queries? Explain compression advantages.', 'OLTP queries access a few rows but all columns per row — row storage is optimal. OLAP queries access millions of rows but only a few columns — column storage is optimal. Column storage: all values for a single column stored together. Analytics query ''SELECT AVG(price) FROM orders WHERE product_id = 42'' only needs to read the price and product_id columns — skips all other columns. Row storage would read entire rows including irrelevant columns. Compression: values in a column are often repetitive (e.g., product_id in orders has high repetition). Column data compresses extremely well: Bitmap encoding: for each distinct value in a column, store a bitmap (one bit per row). Efficient for low-cardinality columns. Run-length encoding: ''AAABBBAAAA'' → ''3A 3B 4A''. Excellent for sorted columns. Result: compressed columns fit more data in CPU cache → less I/O → faster analytics. Column stores can also vectorize operations: apply aggregation functions to compressed column data directly without decompressing. Sort order: rows can be sorted by a primary column — allows run-length encoding on the first sort key; also useful for WHERE clauses on that column. Different sort orders can be maintained as different ''projections'' (C-Store, Vertica). Used by: Amazon Redshift, Snowflake, BigQuery, ClickHouse, Apache Parquet format.', 'storage_engines', 'OLTP-vs-OLAP', 'L4'),
('str-001', 'What is a stream processing event, and how does stream processing differ from batch processing?', 'An event is a small, self-contained, immutable object describing something that happened at a point in time (user action, sensor reading, database write). Unlike batch processing (runs on bounded input files periodically), stream processing handles unbounded, continuously arriving events in real time. Key difference: batch = read input file, produce output file, repeat; stream = react to events as they arrive, produce continuous output. In streaming: events are produced by a producer/publisher, grouped into topics/streams, consumed by multiple consumers/subscribers. Low-latency: instead of polling (expensive), consumers are notified when new events appear.', 'stream_processing', 'basics', 'L1'),
('str-002', 'What is a message broker, and how does it differ from a database?', 'A message broker (message queue) is a server-based intermediary: producers write messages to it, consumers receive messages from it. Brokers tolerate clients going offline — durability moves to the broker. Key differences from databases: (1) Brokers auto-delete messages after delivery — not meant for permanent storage; databases keep data until explicitly deleted. (2) Brokers assume small working set — slow consumers can cause performance degradation as queues grow; databases handle large datasets natively. (3) Brokers notify clients when new data arrives; databases return point-in-time snapshots. (4) Brokers support topic subscriptions; databases support secondary indexes and arbitrary queries. Multiple consumer patterns: Load balancing — each message to one consumer (share processing work); Fan-out — each message to all consumers (multiple independent views of same data). Implemented by: RabbitMQ, ActiveMQ, IBM MQ, Azure Service Bus (AMQP/JMS protocol).', 'stream_processing', 'messaging', 'L1'),
('str-003', 'How does Kafka''s log-based message broker work? How does it differ from traditional AMQP brokers?', 'Kafka architecture: log-based append-only storage. Topics are partitioned; each partition is an append-only log on disk. Messages get a monotonically increasing offset per partition. Producers append to end; consumers read sequentially from their last offset. Consumer groups: each partition assigned to one consumer in a group — partition is the unit of parallelism (max consumers = num partitions). Key differences from AMQP: (1) Messages not deleted after consumption — consumers track their own offset. A slow consumer doesn''t disrupt others. (2) Replay: rewind offset to reprocess past events — impossible in AMQP (ack deletes message). (3) Log is durably persisted to disk — message throughput stays constant regardless of queue depth (vs AMQP which slows down when spilling to disk). (4) Fan-out free — multiple consumer groups each get all messages independently. (5) Ordering guaranteed within a partition; no cross-partition ordering. Kafka throughput: millions of messages/sec via partitioning across machines. Log retention: disk-bounded circular buffer — typically days to weeks of history. Used in: LinkedIn (origin), Uber, Netflix, Confluent.', 'stream_processing', 'kafka', 'L2'),
('str-004', 'What is Change Data Capture (CDC) and how does it differ from Event Sourcing?', 'Change Data Capture (CDC): extracting changes from a database''s replication log and streaming them to other systems (search indexes, caches, data warehouses) to keep them in sync. The database is the system of record; CDC makes its changes available as a stream. Implementation: parse MySQL binlog, PostgreSQL logical replication, Debezium, Kafka Connect. Benefit: avoids dual-write bugs (writing to DB + cache atomically) — instead derive the cache from the DB change stream. Event Sourcing: application stores all state changes as an immutable log of events (events are first-class, the application explicitly appends them). Current state is derived by replaying events. CDC is retrofitted (extract changes from DB); Event Sourcing is designed-in (events are the source of truth). Shared idea (log as truth): both treat the log as the authoritative record. State is derived from the log, not the other way around. Analogy: accounting ledger (append debits/credits) → account balance (derived). Git (commits = events) → working tree (derived state).', 'stream_processing', 'CDC', 'L2'),
('str-005', 'What are the three types of stream joins? What is the challenge of time in stream processing (event time vs processing time)?', 'Three stream join types: (1) Stream-stream join (windowed): join events from two streams that occurred within the same time window. Example: correlate search queries with ad clicks within 1 hour. Both streams must be buffered in state for the window duration. (2) Stream-table join (stream enrichment): enrich a stream event with data from a slowly-changing database table. Load table into operator state; look up on each event. (3) Table-table join (materialized view maintenance): both inputs are change streams from databases; maintain a materialized join view that updates as either table changes. Time challenge — event time vs processing time: Event time: when the event actually occurred (timestamp in the event). Processing time: when the event was processed by the stream processor. They diverge due to: network delays, device clock skew, offline devices sending batched events later. Solution: watermarks — a heuristic assertion that all events with timestamp < T have been received. Allows closing windows and emitting results. Late events after watermark: either drop them, update results (requires downstream to handle corrections), or use a long enough window to absorb expected delays.', 'stream_processing', 'stream-joins', 'L3'),
('str-006', 'How do stream processors achieve fault tolerance and exactly-once semantics?', 'Challenge: stream processing must tolerate failures without losing or duplicating events. Delivery guarantees: At-most-once: process and move on; if failure, lost (lowest overhead). At-least-once: retry on failure — events may be processed multiple times. Exactly-once: hardest — every event processed exactly once even under failures. Achieving exactly-once: (1) Idempotent operations: design processing so re-applying an event produces the same result (no harm from re-execution). Example: SET balance = 100 is idempotent; ADD 10 to balance is not. (2) Atomic commit: commit processed output AND consumer offset atomically (Kafka transactions). If output commits but offset doesn''t → reprocess → but if idempotent, no harm. (3) Micro-batching (Spark Streaming): break stream into small batches (e.g., 1-second intervals), process as batch jobs with batch fault-tolerance guarantees. Exactly-once per micro-batch; latency = batch size. (4) Checkpointing (Apache Flink): periodically snapshot all operator state to durable storage. On failure: restart from last checkpoint, replay events since checkpoint offset. Flink achieves true exactly-once with Chandy-Lamport distributed snapshots. Trade-off: higher exactly-once overhead vs. lower at-least-once overhead. For most analytics (counting, averaging), at-least-once + idempotent aggregations is sufficient. For financial operations, exactly-once is required.', 'stream_processing', 'fault-tolerance', 'L4'),
('tx-001', 'What does ACID stand for, and what does each property actually guarantee?', 'A — Atomicity: all writes in a transaction succeed or all are aborted. If anything fails mid-transaction, partial writes are rolled back. (''All or nothing'') C — Consistency: the application''s invariants are maintained (e.g., account debits must be balanced by credits). Actually a property of the APPLICATION, not the database — the database provides the other three, but consistency is up to you. I — Isolation: concurrently executing transactions appear as if they ran serially. One transaction cannot see another transaction''s uncommitted data (to varying degrees depending on isolation level). D — Durability: once a transaction is committed, its data will not be lost even in the event of a crash. Typically implemented via write-ahead log (WAL) flushed to disk before acknowledging commit.', 'transactions', 'ACID', 'L1'),
('tx-002', 'Describe the four common transaction isolation levels and the anomalies each prevents or permits.', '1. Read Uncommitted: transactions can read uncommitted writes from other transactions (dirty reads). Prevents: nothing meaningful. Used rarely. 2. Read Committed: prevents dirty reads (only see committed data) and dirty writes (don''t overwrite uncommitted data). Common default (PostgreSQL, Oracle). Still allows non-repeatable reads (data changes between two reads in same tx) and phantoms. 3. Snapshot Isolation (Repeatable Read): each transaction reads from a consistent snapshot taken at transaction start. Prevents dirty reads, non-repeatable reads, and most phantoms. Implemented with MVCC (multi-version concurrency control) — reads don''t block writers; writers don''t block readers. Still allows write skew anomalies. Default in PostgreSQL (''repeatable read''), MySQL InnoDB. 4. Serializable: strongest — transactions execute as if completely serial. Prevents all anomalies including write skew. Implemented via: actual serial execution (VoltDB, Redis), two-phase locking (2PL, older DBs), or Serializable Snapshot Isolation (SSI, modern — optimistic approach).', 'transactions', 'isolation-levels', 'L2'),
('tx-003', 'What is write skew? Give a concrete example and explain why snapshot isolation doesn''t prevent it.', 'Write skew: two transactions read the same data, each makes a decision based on what it read, and each writes to different objects. The combined result violates an invariant that neither transaction individually violated. Example (on-call doctors): Transaction A reads: 2 doctors on call (Alice, Bob). Invariant: at least 1 must be on call. A decides to remove Alice (still 1 left). Transaction B simultaneously reads: 2 doctors on call. B decides to remove Bob (still 1 left). Both commit. Result: 0 doctors on call — invariant violated. Why snapshot isolation fails: A and B each read a snapshot where both doctors are on call. Neither sees the other''s write. Each transaction is individually valid from its snapshot''s perspective. Snapshot isolation only sees a consistent snapshot at START of transaction — it doesn''t see writes made by concurrent transactions during execution. Solution: serializable isolation (e.g., SSI or 2PL), or materializing the conflict (add a row for ''on-call slot'' that both transactions write to, turning write skew into a write-write conflict detectable by snapshot isolation).', 'transactions', 'concurrency-anomalies', 'L2'),
('tx-004', 'Compare Two-Phase Locking (2PL) and Serializable Snapshot Isolation (SSI) for achieving serializability.', 'Two-Phase Locking (2PL) — pessimistic: readers acquire shared locks; writers acquire exclusive locks. A writer blocks all readers and writers; a reader blocks writers (but not other readers). Phase 1 (expanding): acquire locks as needed. Phase 2 (shrinking): release locks only after commit/abort. Pros: prevents all anomalies; no conflicts — all serialized. Cons: poor throughput under contention; deadlocks (transactions waiting for each other''s locks — need detection and rollback); readers block writers and vice versa. Serializable Snapshot Isolation (SSI) — optimistic: transactions proceed with snapshot reads (no blocking). At commit time, SSI detects if any transaction read data that was modified by a concurrent transaction (detects ''stale reads''). If so, abort and retry. Pros: reads never block writes; much better throughput for read-heavy workloads. Cons: higher abort rate under high contention (wasted work on transactions that will be retried); requires tracking read sets. Used by: PostgreSQL (serializable isolation level since v9.1), FoundationDB, CockroachDB.', 'transactions', '2PL-SSI', 'L2'),
('tx-005', 'In practice, why do most applications use snapshot isolation rather than full serializability, and when is this dangerous?', 'Why most use snapshot isolation (not serializability): Serializability (2PL) has significant performance cost — lock contention slows throughput, deadlocks require retries, readers block writers. SSI is better but still has abort overhead. Snapshot isolation is fast and prevents most common anomalies (dirty reads, non-repeatable reads) with MVCC — readers and writers don''t block each other. Dangerous cases where snapshot isolation is insufficient: (1) Write skew scenarios (see on-call doctor example) — common in booking systems, constraint enforcement, account balance checks. (2) Phantoms: a transaction reads a set of rows matching a condition; another transaction inserts rows matching that condition; first transaction makes decisions based on incomplete picture. (3) Any multi-object invariant that spans multiple rows/tables. Rule: if your application has invariants that involve reads and writes across multiple objects by concurrent transactions, snapshot isolation is not enough — use serializable isolation or redesign to avoid the race condition (pessimistic locks, atomic compare-and-set operations, or serializable DBs).', 'transactions', 'isolation-levels', 'L3'),
('tx-006', 'Design a hotel room booking system that prevents double-booking, where two users simultaneously try to book the last available room.', 'Race condition: User A reads available rooms → 1 room left → decides to book. User B reads available rooms → 1 room left → decides to book. Both commit → double-booked. Solutions by isolation level: Read committed (no fix): both transactions can commit — classic double-booking. Snapshot isolation (no fix): each transaction sees snapshot at start — both see 1 room available, both book. Write skew anomaly. Serializability (fixes): with 2PL, one booking transaction acquires an exclusive lock; the other waits. With SSI, one transaction detects its snapshot was stale (other committed a booking) and aborts. Application-level fixes (if stuck with weaker isolation): (1) SELECT FOR UPDATE: explicitly lock the booking row before reading — ''SELECT * FROM rooms WHERE id=? FOR UPDATE''. Forces sequential execution. (2) Materialized conflict: insert a ''reservation attempt'' row for the room+date — two attempts create a write-write conflict detectable by snapshot isolation. (3) Atomic compare-and-set: UPDATE rooms SET booked=true WHERE id=? AND booked=false; check affected rows count. Fails atomically if another transaction already booked. Best practice: use a DB that supports serializable isolation (PostgreSQL, CockroachDB) and enable it for booking transactions — accept slightly lower throughput for correctness guarantees.', 'transactions', 'concurrency-anomalies', 'L4')
